{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659214"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:04:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:04:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20857"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20857"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.71,0.06,0.02,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13732"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96468"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13732"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20857"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79110"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"7687"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"12340"},{"type":"tags","id":"12676"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33052"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33053"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96468"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFlow cytometry is a laboratory technique used to analyze cellular characteristics in various clinical and research applications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a key principle of flow cytometry?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Measures only one cellular antigen at a time","Simultaneously detects multiple antigens on individual cells","Primarily used for solid tumor classification","Requires fixed tissue sections for analysis","Relies on enzymatic detection of cellular proteins"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFlow cytometry \u003Cstrong\u003Esimultaneously detects multiple antigens on individual cells\u003C/strong\u003E using combinations of specific antibodies linked to different fluorescent dyes. This allows for comprehensive immunophenotyping of cell populations based on their surface and intracellular markers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires fixed tissue sections for analysis\u003C/strong\u003E - Flow cytometry actually requires viable cells in suspension, not fixed tissue sections. Fixed tissue sections are used in immunohistochemistry.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasures only one cellular antigen at a time\u003C/strong\u003E - A key advantage of flow cytometry is its ability to measure multiple antigens simultaneously on the same cell.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimarily used for solid tumor classification\u003C/strong\u003E - Flow cytometry is mainly used for analyzing hematologic malignancies (\u0022liquid tumors\u0022) such as leukemias and lymphomas, not solid tumors.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelies on enzymatic detection of cellular proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Flow cytometry uses fluorescently-labeled antibodies for detection, not enzymatic reactions.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFlow cytometry is particularly valuable for diagnosing and classifying hematologic malignancies including B-cell and T-cell lymphomas, leukemias, and myeloid neoplasms because these cells are naturally in suspension or can be easily suspended.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Flow cytometry rapidly measures multiple cellular characteristics simultaneously using fluorescently-labeled antibodies against specific antigens.","Flow cytometry requires viable cells in suspension, making it particularly suitable for analyzing hematologic malignancies.","Flow cytometry allows for the identification of specific cell populations based on their immunophenotypic profiles, which is valuable for diagnosing and classifying blood cell neoplasms."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; pages 332-333."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79110"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20857"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79110"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T17:19:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T17:19:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13732"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96468"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7687"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Flow cytometry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-31T13:16:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T13:16:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11597"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neoplasia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":6,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30"},"relation